      "code_changes": [
        {
          "content": "{\n  \"files\": [\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"llvm/llvm-project\",\n      \"path\": \"compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_interceptors.cpp\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"llvm/llvm-project\",\n      \"path\": \"compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_rtl.cpp\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"llvm/llvm-project\",\n      \"path\": \"llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"gcc-mirror/gcc\",\n      \"path\": \"gcc/asan.cc\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"gcc-mirror/gcc\",\n      \"path\": \"gcc/asan.h\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"symbols\": [\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"llvm/llvm-project\",\n      \"path\": \"compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_interceptors.cpp\",\n      \"symbol\": \"INTERCEPTOR\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"llvm/llvm-project\",\n      \"path\": \"compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_rtl.cpp\",\n      \"symbol\": \"AsanInitFromRtl\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"llvm/llvm-project\",\n      \"path\": \"llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp\",\n      \"symbol\": \"ModuleAddressSanitizer\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"gcc-mirror/gcc\",\n      \"path\": \"gcc/asan.cc\",\n      \"symbol\": \"pass_asan\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"gcc-mirror/gcc\",\n      \"path\": \"gcc/asan.cc\",\n      \"symbol\": \"asan_instrument\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"text\": \"AddressSanitizer is implemented in both LLVM and GCC with distinct architectural approaches. In LLVM (llvm-project), ASan functionality is split across three key components: (1) asan_interceptors.cpp in compiler-rt/lib/asan/ defines interceptors for standard library functions using the INTERCEPTOR macro, which wraps functions like malloc, free, and pthread operations to instrument memory accesses. (2) asan_rtl.cpp in compiler-rt/lib/asan/ implements the ASan runtime library initialization through the AsanInitFromRtl() function, which sets up shadow memory, thread tracking, and poison state management. (3) AddressSanitizer.cpp in llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/ implements the LLVM IR-level instrumentation pass via the ModuleAddressSanitizer class, which inserts runtime checks before memory operations by analyzing the intermediate representation. In GCC (gcc-mirror/gcc), ASan instrumentation is consolidated in two files: (1) asan.cc contains the main instrumentation logic, with the pass_asan class implementing the GCC gimple-level pass and the asan_instrument() function orchestrating the transformation of gimple statements to add memory checks. (2) asan.h provides the interface declarations for ASan functions and data structures used throughout GCC's compilation pipeline. The cross-compiler implementations demonstrate parallel evolution of the same sanitizer with compiler-specific optimizations: LLVM operates at IR level with separate runtime initialization, while GCC instruments at the gimple level with integrated pass management.\"\n}\n",
